The Federal Government has vowed to come down hard on all collaborators involved with the Indigenous People of Biafra (IPOB) group and its Leader, Nnamdi Kanu irrespective of their standing in the society.  Minister of Information and Culture, Lai Mohammed who made the declaration during a press conference today in Abuja, said forensic investigation carried out so far has revealed a treasure trove of information on the proscribed IPOB leader and his collaborators  He also declared that Nnamdi Kanu will get a fair hearing as he faces an 11-count charge of treason, treasonable felony, terrorism and illegal possession of firearms, among others.  The Minister reiterated that Nnamdi Kanuâ€™s arrest was made possible by the diligent efforts of security and intelligence agencies, in collaboration with countries with which they have obligations.